# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fault-tree-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] ETA is a powerful tool that will identify all consequences of a system that have a probability of occurring after an initiating event that can be applied to a wide range of systems including: nuclear power plants, spacecraft, and chemical plants.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] This technique may be applied to a system early in the design process to identify potential issues that may arise, rather than correcting the issues after they occur.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] With this forward logic process, use of ETA as a tool in risk assessment can help to prevent negative outcomes from occurring, by providing a risk assessor with the probability of occurrence.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] ETA uses a type of modeling technique called "event tree", which branches events from one single event using Boolean logic.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The name "Event Tree" was first introduced during the WASH-1400 nuclear power plant safety study (circa 1974), where the WASH-1400 team needed an alternate method to fault tree analysis due to the fault trees being too large.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] Though not using the name event tree, the UKAEA first introduced ETA in its design offices in 1968, initially to try to use whole plant risk assessment to optimize the design of a 500MW Steam-Generating Heavy Water Reactor.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] This study showed ETA condensed the analysis into a manageable form.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] ETA was not initially developed during WASH-1400, this was one of the first cases in which it was thoroughly used.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The UKAEA study used the assumption that protective systems either worked or failed, with the probability of failure per demand being calculated using fault trees or similar analysis methods.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] ETA identifies all sequences which follow an initiating event.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] Many of these sequences can be eliminated from the analysis because their frequency or effect are too small to affect the overall result.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] A paper presented at a CREST symposium in Munich, Germany, in 1971 indicated how this was done.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The conclusions of the US EPA study of the Draft WASH-1400 acknowledges the role of Ref 1 and its criticism of the Maximum Credible Accident approach used by AEC.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] MCA sets the reliability target for the containment but those for all other safety systems are set by smaller but more frequent accidents and would be missed by MCA.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] In 2009 a risk analysis was conducted on underwater tunnel excavation under the Han River in Korea using an earth pressure balance type tunnel boring machine.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] ETA was used to quantify risk, by providing the probability of occurrence of an event, in the preliminary design stages of the tunnel construction to prevent any injuries or fatalities because tunnel construction in Korea has the highest injury and fatality rates within the construction category.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] Performing a probabilistic risk assessment starts with a set of initiating events that change the state or configuration of the system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] An initiating event is an event that starts a reaction, such as the way a spark (initiating event) can start a fire that could lead to other events (intermediate events) such as a tree burning down, and then finally an outcome, for example, the burnt tree no longer provides apples for food.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] Each initiating event leads to another event and continuing through this path, where each intermediate event's probability of occurrence may be calculated by using fault tree analysis, until an end state is reached (the outcome of a tree no longer providing apples for food).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] Intermediate events are commonly split into a binary (success/failure or yes/no) but may be split into more than two as long as the events are mutually exclusive, meaning that they can not occur at the same time.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] If a spark is the initiating event there is a probability that the spark will start a fire or will not start a fire (binary yes or no) as well as the probability that the fire spreads to a tree or does not spread to a tree.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] End states are classified into groups that can be successes or severity of consequences.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] An example of a success would be that no fire started and the tree still provided apples for food while the severity of consequence would be that a fire did start and we lose apples as a source of food.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] Loss end states can be any state at the end of the pathway that is a negative outcome of the initiating event.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The loss end state is highly dependent upon the system, for example if you were measuring a quality process in a factory a loss or end state would be that the product has to be reworked or thrown in the trash.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The overall goal of event tree analysis is to determine the probability of possible negative outcomes that can cause harm and result from the chosen initiating event.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] It is necessary to use detailed information about a system to understand intermediate events, accident scenarios, and initiating events to construct the event tree diagram.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The event tree begins with the initiating event where consequences of this event follow in a binary (success/failure) manner.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] Each event creates a path in which a series of successes or failures will occur where the overall probability of occurrence for that path can be calculated.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The probabilities of failures for intermediate events can be calculated using fault tree analysis and the probability of success can be calculated from 1 = probability of success (ps) + probability of failure (pf).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] For example, in the equation 1 = (ps) + (pf) if we know that pf=.1 from fault tree analysis then through simple algebra we can solve for ps where ps = (1) - (pf) then we would have ps = (1) - (.1) and ps=.9.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The event tree diagram models all possible pathways from the initiating event.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The initiating event starts at the left side as a horizontal line that branches vertically. the vertical branch is representative of the success/failure of the initiating event.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] This process continues until the end state is reached.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] When the event tree diagram has reached the end state for all pathways the outcome probability equation is written.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] **Identify the accident scenarios:** Perform a system assessment to find hazards or accident scenarios within the system design.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] **Identify the initiating events:** Use a hazard analysis to define initiating events.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] **Identify intermediate events:** Identify countermeasures associated with the specific scenario.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] **Obtain event failure probabilities:** If the failure probability can not be obtained use fault tree analysis to calculate it.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] **Identify the outcome risk:** Calculate the overall probability of the event paths and determine the risk.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] **Evaluate the outcome risk:** Evaluate the risk of each path and determine its acceptability.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] **Recommend corrective action:** If the outcome risk of a path is not acceptable develop design changes that change the risk.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] **Document the ETA:** Document the entire process on the event tree diagrams and update for new information as needed.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The probability of success can be derived from the probability of failure.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The event tree analysis can be used in risk assessments by determining the probability that is used to determine risk when multiply by the hazard of events.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] Event Tree Analysis makes it easy to see what pathway creating the biggest probability of failure for a specific system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] It is common to find single-point failures that do not have any intervening events between the initiating event and a failure.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] With Event Tree Analysis single-point failure can be targeted to include an intervening step that will reduce the overall probability of failure and thus reducing the risk of the system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] The idea of adding an intervening event can happen anywhere in the system for any pathway that generates too great of a risk, the added intermediate event can reduce the probability and thus reduce the risk.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] Though ETA can be relatively simple, software can be used for more complex systems to build the diagram and perform calculations more quickly with reduction of human errors in the process.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] There are many types of software available to assist in conducting an ETA.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] In nuclear industry, RiskSpectrum software is widely used which has both event tree analysis and fault tree analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] Professional-grade free software solutions are also widely available.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/event-tree-analysis] SCRAM is an example open-source tool that implements the Open-PSA Model Exchange Format open standard for probabilistic safety assessment applications.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] In aerospace, the more general term "system failure condition" is used for the "undesired state" / top event of the fault tree.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] These conditions are classified by the severity of their effects.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The most severe conditions require the most extensive fault tree analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] These system failure conditions and their classification are often previously determined in the functional hazard analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Fault tree analysis (FTA) was originally developed in 1962 at Bell Laboratories by H.A.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Air Force Ballistics Systems Division contract to evaluate the Minuteman I Intercontinental Ballistic Missile (ICBM) Launch Control System.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The use of fault trees has since gained widespread support and is often used as a failure analysis tool by reliability experts.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Following the first published use of FTA in the 1962 Minuteman I Launch Control Safety Study, Boeing and AVCO expanded use of FTA to the entire Minuteman II system in 1963–1964.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] FTA received extensive coverage at a 1965 System Safety Symposium in Seattle sponsored by Boeing and the University of Washington.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Boeing began using FTA for civil aircraft design around 1966.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Subsequently, within the U.S. military, application of FTA for use with fuses was explored by Picatinny Arsenal in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Army Materiel Command incorporated FTA into an Engineering Design Handbook on Design for Reliability.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] MIL-HDBK-338B provides a more recent reference.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) published a change to 14 CFR 25.1309 airworthiness regulations for transport category aircraft in the Federal Register at 35 FR 5665 (1970-04-08).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] This change adopted failure probability criteria for aircraft systems and equipment and led to widespread use of FTA in civil aviation.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] In 1998, the FAA published Order 8040.4, establishing risk management policy including hazard analysis in a range of critical activities beyond aircraft certification, including air traffic control and modernization of the U.S.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] This led to the publication of the FAA System Safety Handbook, which describes the use of FTA in various types of formal hazard analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Early in the Apollo program the question was asked about the probability of successfully sending astronauts to the moon and returning them safely to Earth.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] A risk, or reliability, calculation of some sort was performed and the result was a mission success probability that was unacceptably low.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] This result discouraged NASA from further quantitative risk or reliability analysis until after the *Challenger* accident in 1986.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Instead, NASA decided to rely on the use of failure modes and effects analysis (FMEA) and other qualitative methods for system safety assessments.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] After the *Challenger* accident, the importance of probabilistic risk assessment (PRA) and FTA in systems risk and reliability analysis was realized and its use at NASA has begun to grow and now FTA is considered as one of the most important system reliability and safety analysis techniques.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Within the nuclear power industry, the U.S.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Nuclear Regulatory Commission began using PRA methods including FTA in 1975, and significantly expanded PRA research following the 1979 incident at Three Mile Island.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] This eventually led to the 1981 publication of the NRC Fault Tree Handbook NUREG–0492, and mandatory use of PRA under the NRC's regulatory authority.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] OSHA PSM recognizes FTA as an acceptable method for process hazard analysis (PHA).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Today FTA is widely used in system safety and reliability engineering, and in all major fields of engineering.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Any sufficiently complex system is subject to failure as a result of one or more subsystems failing.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The likelihood of failure, however, can often be reduced through improved system design.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Fault tree analysis maps the relationship between faults, subsystems, and redundant safety design elements by creating a logic diagram of the overall system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The undesired outcome is taken as the root ('top event') of a tree of logic.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] For instance, the undesired outcome of a metal stamping press operation being considered might be a human appendage being stamped.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Working backward from this top event it might be determined that there are two ways this could happen: during normal operation or during maintenance operation.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Considering the branch of the hazard occurring during normal operation, perhaps it is determined that there are two ways this could happen: the press cycles and harms the operator, or the press cycles and harms another person.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] A design improvement can be made by requiring the operator to press two separate buttons to cycle the machine—this is a safety feature in the form of a logical AND.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The button may have an intrinsic failure rate—this becomes a fault stimulus that can be analyzed.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] When fault trees are labeled with actual numbers for failure probabilities, computer programs can calculate failure probabilities from fault trees.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] When a specific event is found to have more than one effect event, i.e. it has impact on several subsystems, it is called a common cause or common mode.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Graphically speaking, it means this event will appear at several locations in the tree.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Common causes introduce dependency relations between events.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The probability computations of a tree which contains some common causes are much more complicated than regular trees where all events are considered as independent.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Not all software tools available on the market provide such capability.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The tree is usually written out using conventional logic gate symbols.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] A cut set is a combination of events, typically component failures, causing the top event.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] If no event can be removed from a cut set without failing to cause the top event, then it is called a minimal cut set.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Some industries use both fault trees and event trees (see Probabilistic Risk Assessment).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] An event tree starts from an undesired initiator (loss of critical supply, component failure etc.) and follows possible further system events through to a series of final consequences.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] As each new event is considered, a new node on the tree is added with a split of probabilities of taking either branch.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The probabilities of a range of 'top events' arising from the initial event can then be seen.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Classic programs include the Electric Power Research Institute's (EPRI) CAFTA software, which is used by many of the US nuclear power plants and by a majority of US and international aerospace manufacturers, and the Idaho National Laboratory's SAPHIRE, which is used by the U.S.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Government to evaluate the safety and reliability of nuclear reactors, the Space Shuttle, and the International Space Station.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Outside the US, the software RiskSpectrum is a popular tool for fault tree and event tree analysis, and is licensed for use at more than 60% of the world's nuclear power plants for probabilistic safety assessment.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Professional-grade free software is also widely available; SCRAM is an open-source tool that implements the Open-PSA Model Exchange Format open standard for probabilistic safety assessment applications.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The basic symbols used in FTA are grouped as events, gates, and transfer symbols.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Minor variations may be used in FTA software.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Event symbols are used for *primary events* and *intermediate events*.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Primary events are not further developed on the fault tree.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Intermediate events are found at the output of a gate.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] An intermediate event gate can be used immediately above a primary event to provide more room to type the event description.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Gate symbols describe the relationship between input and output events.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Transfer symbols are used to connect the inputs and outputs of related fault trees, such as the fault tree of a subsystem to its system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] NASA prepared a complete document about FTA through practical incidents.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Events in a fault tree are associated with statistical probabilities or Poisson-Exponentially distributed constant rates.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] For example, component failures may typically occur at some constant failure rate λ (a constant hazard function).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] A fault tree is often normalized to a given time interval, such as a flight hour or an average mission time.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Event probabilities depend on the relationship of the event hazard function to this interval.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Unlike conventional logic gate diagrams in which inputs and outputs hold the binary values of TRUE (1) or FALSE (0), the gates in a fault tree output probabilities related to the set operations of Boolean logic.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The probability of a gate's output event depends on the input event probabilities.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] An AND gate represents a combination of independent events.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] That is, the probability of any input event to an AND gate is unaffected by any other input event to the same gate.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Again, since P (A ∩ B) usually becomes a very small error term, the exclusive OR gate has limited value in a fault tree.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Quite often, Poisson-Exponentially distributed rates are used to quantify a fault tree instead of probabilities.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Rates are often modeled as constant in time while probability is a function of time.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Poisson-Exponential events are modelled as infinitely short so no two events can overlap.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] An OR gate is the superposition (addition of rates) of the two input failure frequencies or failure rates which are modeled as Poisson point processes.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The output of an AND gate is calculated using the unavailability (Q1) of one event thinning the Poisson point process of the other event (λ2).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The unavailability (Q2) of the other event then thins the Poisson point process of the first event (λ1).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The two resulting Poisson point processes are superimposed according to the following equations.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] In a fault tree, unavailability (Q) may be defined as the unavailability of safe operation and may not refer to the unavailability of the system operation depending on how the fault tree was structured.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] The input terms to the fault tree must be carefully defined.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Many different approaches can be used to model a FTA, but the most common and popular way can be summarized in a few steps.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] A single fault tree is used to analyze one and only one undesired event, which may be subsequently fed into another fault tree as a basic event.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Though the nature of the undesired event may vary dramatically, a FTA follows the same procedure for any undesired event; be it a delay of 0.25 ms for the generation of electrical power, an undetected cargo bay fire, or the random, unintended launch of an ICBM.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] FTA is a deductive, top-down method aimed at analyzing the effects of initiating faults and events on a complex system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] This contrasts with failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA), which is an inductive, bottom-up analysis method aimed at analyzing the effects of single component or function failures on equipment or subsystems.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] FTA is very good at showing how resistant a system is to single or multiple initiating faults.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] It is not good at finding all possible initiating faults.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] FMEA is good at exhaustively cataloging initiating faults, and identifying their local effects.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] It is not good at examining multiple failures or their effects at a system level.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] FTA considers external events, FMEA does not.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] In civil aerospace the usual practice is to perform both FTA and FMEA, with a failure mode effects summary (FMES) as the interface between FMEA and FTA.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] Alternatives to FTA include dependence diagram (DD), also known as reliability block diagram (RBD) and Markov analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] A dependence diagram is equivalent to a success tree analysis (STA), the logical inverse of an FTA, and depicts the system using paths instead of gates.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/fault-tree-analysis] DD and STA produce probability of success (i.e., avoiding a top event) rather than probability of a top event.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] A **hazard and operability study** (HAZOP) is a structured and systematic examination of a complex system, usually a process facility or machinery, in order to identify hazards to personnel, equipment or the environment, as well as operability problems that could affect operations efficiency.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] It is the foremost hazard identification tool in the domain of process safety.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The technique is based on breaking the overall complex design of the process into a number of simpler sections called *nodes* which are then individually reviewed.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] It is carried out by a suitably experienced multi-disciplinary team (roles defined in section below) during a series of meetings.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The HAZOP technique is qualitative and aims to stimulate the imagination of participants to identify potential hazards and operability problems.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Structure and direction are given to the review process by applying standardized guideword prompts to the review of each node.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The HAZOP technique was initially developed for systems involving the treatment of a fluid medium or other material flow in the process industries, where it is now a major element of process safety management.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] It was later expanded to the analysis of batch reactions and process plant operational procedures.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The technique is generally considered to have originated in the Heavy Organic Chemicals Division of Imperial Chemical Industries (ICI), which was then a major British and international chemical company.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Its origins have been described by Trevor Kletz, who was the company's safety advisor from 1968 to 1982.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] In 1963 a team of three people met for three days a week for four months to study the design of a new phenol plant, starting with a technique called *critical examination* which asked for alternatives but later changed this to ask for *deviations*.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The method was further refined within the company, under the name *operability studies*, and became the third stage, detailed design, of its hazard analysis procedure (the first two stages being done during conception and specification).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] In 1974 a one-week safety course including this procedure was offered by the Institution of Chemical Engineers (IChemE) at Teesside Polytechnic.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Coming shortly after the Flixborough disaster, the course was fully booked, as were ones in the next few years.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] In the same year as the 1974 course offering, the first paper in open literature was also published.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] In 1977 the Chemical Industries Association published a guide.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Up to this time the term 'HAZOP' had not been used in formal publications.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The first to do this was Kletz in 1983, with what were essentially the course notes (revised and updated) from the IChemE courses.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] By 1983, hazard and operability studies had become an expected part of chemical engineering degree courses in the UK.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Nowadays, government regulators (EPA, OSHA, etc.) and the process industry at large (including operators and contractors) consider HAZOP a strictly necessary step of project development, at the very least during the detailed design phase.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The method is applied to complex processes, for which sufficient design information is available and not likely to change significantly.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] This range of data should be explicitly identified and taken as the "design intent" basis for the HAZOP study.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] For example, a prudent designer will have intended to allow for foreseeable variations within the process, creating a larger design envelope than just the basic requirements, and the HAZOP will be looking at ways in which this might not be sufficient.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] A common use of the HAZOP is relatively early through the detailed design of a plant or process.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] However, it can also be applied at other stages (operational life) of existing plants, in which case it is usefully applied as a revalidation tool to ensure that unduly managed changes have not crept in since first plant start-up.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] For process plants, identifiable sections (*nodes*) are chosen so that for each a meaningful *design intent* can be specified .
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] They are commonly indicated on piping and instrumentation diagrams (P&IDs) and process flow diagrams (PFDs).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] P&IDs in particular are the foremost reference document for conducting a HAZOP.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The detail of each node should be appropriate to the complexity of the system and the magnitude of the hazards it might pose.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] For each node, the HAZOP team uses a list of standardized *guidewords* and process *parameters* listed in the section below to identify potential *deviations* from the design intent.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The degree of preparation for the HAZOP is critical to the overall success of the review.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] "Frozen" design information provided to the team members with time for them to familiarize themselves with the process, an adequate schedule allowed for the performance of the HAZOP, provision of the best team members for their role.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Those scheduling a HAZOP should take into account the review scope, the number of nodes to be reviewed, the provision of completed design drawings and documentation and the need to maintain team performance over an extended time-frame.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The team members may also need to perform some of their normal tasks during this period and the HAZOP team members can tend to lose focus unless adequate time is allowed for them to refresh their mental capabilities.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The team meetings should be managed by an independent, trained HAZOP *facilitator* (also referred to as HAZOP leader or chairperson), who is responsible for the overall quality of the review, partnered with a dedicated *scribe* to minute the meetings.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] For a medium-sized chemical plant, where the total number of items to be considered is around 1200 pieces of equipment and piping, about 40 such meetings would be needed.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Various software programs are now available to assist in the management and scribing of the HAZOP activities.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] In order to identify deviations, the team applies (systematically i.e. in a given order) a set of **guidewords** to each node in the process.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] To prompt discussion, or to ensure completeness, appropriate process **parameters** are considered in turn, which apply to the design intent.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Typical parameters are flow (or flowrate), temperature, pressure, level, composition, etc.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The IEC standard notes guidewords should be chosen that are appropriate to the study, neither too specific (limiting ideas and discussion) nor too general (allowing loss of focus).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Where a guide word is meaningfully applicable to a parameter (e.g., "no flow", "more temperature"), their combination should be recorded as a credible potential *deviation* from the design intent that requires review.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The following table gives an overview of commonly used guideword-parameter pairs (deviations) and common interpretations of them.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Once the causes and effects of any potential hazards have been established, the system being studied can then be modified to improve its safety.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The modified design should then be subject to a formal HAZOP close-out, to ensure that no new problems have been added.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] The team should be as small as practicable and having relevant skills and experience.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Where a system has been designed by a contractor, the HAZOP team should contain personnel from both the contractor and the client company.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] A minimum team size of five is recommended.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] In a large process there will be many HAZOP meetings and the individuals within the team may change, as different specialists and deputies will be required for the various roles.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] As many as 20 individuals may be involved.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] In earlier publications it was suggested that the study leader could also be the recorder but separate roles are now generally recommended.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/hazard-and-operability-study] Specialist software is now available from several suppliers to support the recording of meeting minutes and tracking the completion of recommended actions.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] A **reliability block diagram (RBD)** is a diagrammatic method for showing how component reliability contributes to the success or failure of a redundant system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] RBD is also known as a dependence diagram (DD).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] An RBD is drawn as a series of blocks connected in parallel or series configuration.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] Parallel blocks indicate redundant subsystems or components that contribute to a lower failure rate.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] Each block represents a component of the system with a failure rate.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] RBDs will indicate the type of redundancy in the parallel path.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] For example, a group of parallel blocks could require two out of three components to succeed for the system to succeed.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] By contrast, any failure along a series path causes the entire series path to fail.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] An RBD may be drawn using switches in place of blocks, where a closed switch represents a working component and an open switch represents a failed component.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] If a path may be found through the network of switches from beginning to end, the system still works.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] An RBD may be converted to a success tree or a fault tree depending on how the RBD is defined.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] A success tree may then be converted to a fault tree or vice versa by applying de Morgan's theorem.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] To evaluate an RBD, closed form solutions are available when blocks or components have *statistical independence*.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] When statistical independence is not satisfied, specific formalisms and solution tools such as dynamic RBD have to be considered.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] The first thing one must determine when calculating an RBD is whether to use probability or rate.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] Failure rates are often used in RBDs to determine system failure rates.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] Use probabilities or rates in an RBD but not both.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] Parallel rates can be evaluated using a number of formulas including this formula for all units active with equal component failure rates.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] *n* − *q* out of *n* redundant units are required for success.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] If the components in a parallel system have *n* different failure rates a more general formula can be used as follows.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/reliability-block-diagram] For the repairable model *Q* = *λ*/*μ* as long as ${\textstyle \mu \gg \lambda }$ .
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In science and reliability engineering, **root-cause analysis** (**RCA**) is a method of problem solving used for identifying the root causes of faults or problems.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] It is widely used in IT operations, manufacturing, telecommunications, industrial process control, accident analysis (e.g., in aviation, rail transport, or nuclear plants), medical diagnosis, the healthcare industry (e.g., for epidemiology).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is a form of inductive inference (first create a theory, or *root*, based on empirical evidence, or *causes*) and deductive inference (test the theory, i.e., the underlying causal mechanisms, with empirical data).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Establish a causal graph between the root-cause and the problem.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA generally serves as input to a remediation process whereby corrective actions are taken to prevent the problem from recurring.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The name of this process varies between application domains.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] According to ISO/IEC 31010, RCA may include these techniques: five whys, failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA), fault tree analysis, Ishikawa diagrams, and Pareto analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] There are essentially two ways of repairing faults and solving problems in science and engineering.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Reactive management consists of reacting quickly after the problem occurs, by treating the symptoms.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This type of management is implemented by reactive systems, self-adaptive systems, self-organized systems, and complex adaptive systems.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The goal here is to react quickly and alleviate the effects of the problem as soon as possible.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Proactive management, conversely, consists of preventing problems from occurring.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Many techniques can be used for this purpose, ranging from good practices in design to analyzing in detail problems that have already occurred and taking actions to make sure they never recur.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Speed is not as important here as the accuracy and precision of the diagnosis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The focus is on addressing the real cause of the problem rather than its effects.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is often used in proactive management to identify the root cause of a problem, that is, the factor that was the leading cause.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] It is customary to refer to the "root cause" in singular form, but one or several factors may constitute the *root cause(s)* of the problem under study.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A factor is considered the "root cause" of a problem if removing it prevents the problem from recurring.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Conversely, a "causal factor" is a contributing action that affects an incident/event's outcome but is not the root cause.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Although removing a causal factor can benefit an outcome, it does not prevent its recurrence with certainty.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A great way to look at the proactive/reactive picture is to consider the Bowtie Risk Assessment model.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In the center of the model is the event or accident.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] To the left, are the anticipated hazards and the line of defenses put in place to prevent those hazards from causing events.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The line of defense is the regulatory requirements, applicable procedures, physical barriers, and cyber barriers that are in place to manage operations and prevent events.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A great way to use root-cause analysis is to proactively evaluate the effectiveness of those defenses by comparing actual performance against applicable requirements, identifying performance gaps, and then closing the gaps to strengthen those defenses.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] If an event occurs, then we are on the right side of the model, the reactive side where the emphasis is on identifying the root causes and mitigating the damage.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Imagine an investigation into a machine that stopped because it was overloaded and the fuse blew.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Investigation shows that the machine was overloaded because it had a bearing that was not being sufficiently lubricated.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The investigation proceeds further and finds that the automatic lubrication mechanism had a pump that was not pumping sufficiently, hence the lack of lubrication.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Investigation of the pump shows that it has a worn shaft.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Investigation of why the shaft was worn discovers that there is not an adequate mechanism to prevent metal scrap getting into the pump; this enabled scrap to get into the pump and damage it.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The apparent root cause of the problem is that metal scrap can contaminate the lubrication system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Fixing this problem ought to prevent the whole sequence of events from recurring.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The *real* root cause could be a design issue if there is no filter to prevent the metal scrap getting into the system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Or if it has a filter that was blocked due to a lack of routine inspection, then the *real* root cause is a maintenance issue.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Compare this with an investigation that does not find the root cause: replacing the fuse, the bearing, or the lubrication pump will probably allow the machine to go back into operation for a while.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] However, there is a risk that the problem will simply recur until the root cause is dealt with.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In general terms, for the investigating team, such as quality and engineering personnel, vernacularly speaking, it commonly takes around 5 times asking "why".
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The above example does not include cost/benefit analysis: does the cost of replacing one or more machines exceed the cost of downtime until the fuse is replaced?
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This situation is sometimes referred to as *the cure being worse than the disease*.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This can help explain the problem of the cure being worse than the disease.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Costs to consider go beyond finances when considering the personnel who operate the machinery.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Ultimately, the goal is to prevent downtime; but more so prevent catastrophic injuries.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Despite the different approaches among the various schools of root-cause analysis and the specifics of each application domain, RCA generally follows the same steps.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Effective problem statements and event descriptions (as failures, for example) are helpful and usually required to ensure the execution of appropriate root-cause analyses.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Problem statements are the North Star of the RCA as it keeps the team focused on what they are investigating and prevents them from going astray.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Most RCAs begin with a fact finding session to gather available information such as witness statements, the chronology of events and applicable requirements for the evolutions that were taking place at the time of the event.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The information can be used to establish a sequence of events or timeline for the event, and to identify the line of the defenses that should have prevented the event (i.e. the administrative requirements, and physical and cyber barriers).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Available databases should also be queried and analyzed (such as corrective action program and safety program databases), and data analysis tools such as Pareto charts, process maps, fault trees, and other tools that provide insights into performance gaps.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Any number of data analysis tools can be brought to bear, including data analysis tools from Lean Six Sigma, statistical analysis tools, and others such as hierarchical clustering and data-mining solutions (such as graph-theory-based data mining).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Another consists in comparing the situation under investigation with past situations stored in case libraries, using case-based reasoning tools and can include change analysis, comparative timeline analysis and task analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] After identifying the defenses in place that should have prevented the event or accident, an analysis of defenses (traditionally called Barrier Analysis) can be conducted in every case, including non-RCA investigations.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] These initial gaps in performance are merely symptoms of deeper-seated causes.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] These symptomatic performance gaps are used to develop lines of inquiry questions as outlined below, to pursue the symptoms back to their points of origin (i.e. the root causes) using cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] After gathering available information, organizing it into charts with timelines and other data, after analyzing available data, and after conducting an analysis of defenses, those insights are used to generate questions.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] These questions become lines of inquiry for cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] There should not be any curiosity questions, questions that reflect "confirmation bias" (i.e. asking a leading question so they answer what the RCA team thinks are the causes), or questions that are accusatory in nature that will cause those helping the investigation to close down and withdraw.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Once a robust set of lines of inquiry questions has been developed from the factual evidence collected, the applicable requirements, and an analysis of the available data, those questions can be taken to the organization's subject matter experts.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This begins the process of cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Once a question is posed to the affected organization, their answer is used to pose a follow-up Socratic questions.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Socratic questions keep the investigation flowing down to the next deeper causal factors until the organization runs out of answers, or the last causal factor is beyond the organization's control.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] There are many skills involved in conducting an effective cause-and-effect analysis, including facilitation skills, communication skills, and Socratic questioning.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] When conducted properly, this will take the RCA down to the deepest-seated root causes.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A word of caution: Ishikawa or the Fishbone Diagram, and the 5-Whys methods, are not rigorous enough for conducting a root-cause analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The Fishbone is from the 1940s and the 5-Whys is from the 1930, and there are much more advanced methods available.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Look for methods that were developed in this century (the year 2000 and later), as they are more likely to account for the new dynamics of the modern sociotechnical work environments.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The best way to chart the results of an RCA investigation is to start populating the final chart from the start.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This process has become much easier with the advent of virtual whiteboards.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In a single virtual whiteboard, the timelines, lines of defenses, data analysis, lines of inquiry questions, cause-and-effect analysis, root causes, and corrective action plan can be displayed.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The Extent of Cause reviews are conducted to determine the extent of the damage or impact that the root causes and contributing factors had on humans, equipment, or facilities.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Extent of Cause reviews are an Achilles heel in the vast majority of organizations and a primary reason why RCAs and corrective action plans fail to prevent recurrence.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Also, care must be taken to avoid corrective action plans that simply add more administrative requirements and more training to the organization.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] To avoid this, use the Hierarchy of Hazard Controls and Lean Mistake Proofing as guidelines for developing effective corrective actions that have a much higher likelihood of preventing recurrence.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] After a pre-determined period after the implementation of the corrective action plan, an effectiveness review is scheduled to evaluate the effectiveness of those corrective actions.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This requires specifying a set of metrics or indicators that will be monitored prior to and after the corrective actions are implemented, so their impact can be measured.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] If the desired results are not achieved, which in most cases is a significant reduction in the magnitude or frequency of the event or problem, then the RCA must be reopened as it was not effective.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] To be effective, root-cause analysis must be performed systematically.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The process enables the chance to not miss any other important details.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A team effort is typically required, and ideally all persons involved should arrive at the same conclusion.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In aircraft accident analyses, for example, the conclusions of the investigation and the root causes that are identified must be backed up by documented evidence.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The goal of RCA is to identify the root cause of the problem with the intent to stop the problem from recurring or worsening.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The next step is to trigger long-term corrective actions to address the root cause identified during RCA, and make sure that the problem does not resurface.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Correcting a problem is not formally part of RCA, however; these are different steps in a problem-solving process known as fault management in IT and telecommunications, repair in engineering, remediation in aviation, environmental remediation in ecology, therapy in medicine, etc.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is used in many application domains.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is specifically called out in the United States Code of Federal Regulations in many of the Titles.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] TITLE 14 - AERONAUTICS AND SPACE >>> 14 CFR Chapter III, Subchapter C, Part 437, Subpart C, §437.73 Anomaly recording, reporting and implementation of corrective actions.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A permittee must identify all root causes of each anomaly and implement all corrective actions for each anomaly.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] TITLE 21 - FOOD AND DRUG >>> 21 CFR Subpart J: 21CFR820.100(a) – Corr./Preventive Action: (A) Each manufacturer shall establish and maintain procedures for implementing corrective and preventive action.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The example above illustrates how RCA can be used in manufacturing.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also routinely used in industrial process control, e.g. to control the production of chemicals (quality control).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used for failure analysis in engineering and maintenance.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is frequently used in IT and telecommunications to detect the root causes of serious problems.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] For example, in the ITIL service management framework, the goal of incident management is to resume a faulty IT service as soon as possible (reactive management), whereas problem management deals with solving recurring problems for good by addressing their root causes (proactive management).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Another example is the computer security incident management process, where root-cause analysis is often used to investigate security breaches.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used in conjunction with business activity monitoring and complex event processing to analyze faults in business processes.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Its use in the IT industry cannot always be compared to its use in safety critical industries, since in normality the use of RCA in IT industry is *not* supported by pre-existing fault trees or other design specs.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Instead a mixture of debugging, event based detection and monitoring systems (where the services are individually modelled) is normally supporting the analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Training and supporting tools like simulation or different in-depth runbooks for all expected scenarios do not exist, instead they are created after the fact based on issues seen as 'worthy'.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] As a result the analysis is often limited to those things that have monitoring/observation interfaces and not the actual planned/seen function with focus on verification of inputs and outputs.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Hence, the saying "there is no root cause" has become common in the IT industry.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In the domains of health and safety, RCA is routinely used in medicine (diagnosis) and epidemiology (e.g., to identify the source of an infectious disease), where causal inference methods often require both clinical and statistical expertise to make sense of the complexities of the processes.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is used in environmental science (e.g., to analyze environmental disasters), accident analysis (aviation and rail industry), and occupational safety and health.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In the manufacture of medical devices, pharmaceuticals, food, and dietary supplements, root-cause analysis is a regulatory requirement.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used in change management, risk management, and systems analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Without delving in the idiosyncrasies of specific problems, several general conditions can make RCA more difficult than it may appear at first sight.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] First, important information is often missing because it is generally not possible, in practice, to monitor everything and store all monitoring data for a long time.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Second, gathering data and evidence, and classifying them along a timeline of events to the final problem, can be nontrivial.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In telecommunications, for instance, distributed monitoring systems typically manage between a million and a billion events per day.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Finding a few relevant events in such a mass of irrelevant events is asking to find the proverbial needle in a haystack.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Third, there may be more than one root cause for a given problem, and this multiplicity can make the causal graph very difficult to establish.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Fourth, causal graphs often have many levels, and root-cause analysis terminates at a level that is "root" to the eyes of the investigator.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Switching vendors may have been due to management's desire to save money, and a failure to consult with engineering staff on the implication of the change on maintenance procedures.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Thus, while the "root cause" shown above may have prevented the quoted recurrence, it would not have prevented other – perhaps more severe – failures affecting other machines.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] A **single point of failure** (**SPOF**) is a part of a system that would stop the entire system from working if it were to fail.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] The term single point of failure implies that there is no backup or redundant option that would enable the system to continue to function without it.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] SPOFs are undesirable in any system with a goal of high availability or reliability, be it a business practice, software application, or other industrial system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] If there is a SPOF present in a system, it produces a potential interruption to the system that is substantially more disruptive than an error would be elsewhere in the system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Systems can be made robust by adding redundancy in all potential SPOFs.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Redundancy can be achieved at various levels.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] The assessment of a potential SPOF involves identifying the critical components of a complex system that would provoke a total systems failure in case of malfunction.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Highly reliable systems should not rely on any such individual component.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] For instance, the owner of a small tree care company may own only one woodchipper.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] If the chipper breaks, they may be unable to complete their current job and may have to cancel future jobs until they can obtain a replacement.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] The owner could prepare for this in multiple ways.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] The owner of the tree care company may have spare parts ready for the repair of the wood chipper, in case it fails.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] At a higher level, they may have a second wood chipper that they can bring to the job site.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Finally, at the highest level, they may have enough equipment available to completely replace everything at the work site in the case of multiple failures.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] A fault-tolerant computer system can be achieved at the internal component level, at the system level (multiple machines), or site level (replication).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] One would normally deploy a load balancer to ensure high availability for a server cluster at the system level.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] In a high-availability server cluster, each individual server may attain internal component redundancy by having multiple power supplies, hard drives, and other components.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] System-level redundancy could be obtained by having spare servers waiting to take on the work of another server if it fails.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Since a data center is often a support center for other operations, such as business logic, it represents a potential SPOF in itself.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Thus, at the site level, the entire cluster may be replicated at another location, where it can be accessed in case the primary location becomes unavailable.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] This is typically addressed as part of an IT disaster recovery program.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] While previously the solution to this SPOF was physical duplication of clusters, the high demand for this duplication led multiple businesses to outsource duplication to 3rd parties using cloud computing.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] It has been argued by scholars, however, that doing so simply moves the SPOF and may even increase the likelihood of a failure or cyberattack.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Paul Baran and Donald Davies developed packet switching, a key part of "survivable communications networks".
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Such networks – including ARPANET and the Internet – are designed to have no single point of failure.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Multiple paths between any two points on the network allow those points to continue communicating with each other, the packets "routing around" damage, even after any single failure of any one particular path or any one intermediate node.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] In software engineering, a **bottleneck** occurs when the capacity of an application or a computer system is limited by a single component.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] The bottleneck has the lowest throughput of all parts of the transaction path.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] A common example is when a used programming language is capable of parallel processing, but a given snippet of code has several independent processes run sequentially rather than simultaneously.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Tracking down bottlenecks (sometimes known as *hot spots* – sections of the code that execute most frequently – i.e., have the highest execution count) is called performance analysis.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Reduction is usually achieved with the help of specialized tools, known as performance analyzers or profilers.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] The objective is to make those particular sections of code perform as fast as possible to improve overall algorithmic efficiency.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] A vulnerability or security exploit in just one component can compromise an entire system.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] One of the largest concerns in computer security is attempting to eliminate SPOFs without sacrificing too much convenience to the user.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] With the invention and popularization of the Internet, several systems became connected to the broader world through many difficult-to-secure connections.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] While companies have developed a number of solutions to this, the most consistent form of SPOFs in complex systems tends to remain user error, either by accidental mishandling by an operator or outside interference through phishing attacks.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] The concept of a single point of failure has also been applied to fields outside of engineering, computers, and networking, such as corporate supply chain management and transportation management.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Design structures that create single points of failure include bottlenecks and series circuits (in contrast to parallel circuits).
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] The concept of a single point of failure has also been applied to the intelligence field, and the processes of intelligence.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] Edward Snowden talked of the dangers of being what he described as "the single point of failure" – the sole repository of information.
[src:fault-tree-analysis/single-point-of-failure] A component of a life-support system that would constitute a single point of failure would be required to be extremely reliable.
